[1] ECDC/WHO
Date: Tue 31 May 2022
Source: European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control [edited]
https://www.ecdc.europa.eu/en/hepatitis/joint-weekly-hepatitis-unknown-origin-children-surveillance-bulletin


Joint ECDC-WHO Regional Office for Europe Hepatitis of Unknown Origin in Children Surveillance Bulletin
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Surveillance summary
-------------------
This report provides an overview of the cases of hepatitis of unknown origin in children aged 16 years and below reported to ECDC and the WHO Regional Office for Europe through The European Surveillance System (TESSy) hosted at ECDC. As of [Tue 31 May 2022], 305 cases of acute hepatitis of unknown etiology in children aged 16 years and below have been reported from the European region, of which 305 were classified as probable and none as epidemiologically linked, by 17 countries (Austria (2), Belgium (14), Bulgaria (1), Cyprus (2), Denmark (7), Greece (5), Ireland (8), Italy (29), the Netherlands (14), Norway (5), Poland (3), Portugal (15), Republic of Moldova (1), Serbia (1), Spain (34), Sweden (9), and the UK (155)).

Since the last surveillance bulletin, which used data as of [Fri 20 May 2022], 29 new cases have been reported from 8 countries (Belgium (1), Bulgaria (1), Greece (2), Italy (2), Poland (2), Portugal (4), Spain (6), and the UK (11)).

The epicurve shows cases by the date of onset of first symptoms of disease when available (171 cases), and the date of hospitalisation (127 cases) or date used for statistics when the former are not available (7 cases). A sustained increase in the number of reported cases occurred from week 51 2021, followed by a sharp rise leading to an observed maximum on weeks 12 and 13 2022. As severe hepatitis can take some time to develop after the onset of the 1st symptoms and as investigations take time, there may be a delay in the reporting of cases. The recent decrease in cases is therefore challenging to interpret.

The majority (76.1%) of cases are 5 years old or younger. Of the 305 probable cases, 180 had reported information on outcome. Of these, 148 have recovered, while 31 remain under medical care. Of 169 cases with information, 23 (13.6%) were admitted to an intensive care unit. Of the 131 cases for which this information was available, 14 (10.7%) have received a liver transplant. There has been 1 death associated with this disease.

Overall, 199 cases were tested for adenovirus by any specimen type and had a valid positive or negative result. Of these, 118 (59.3%) tested positive. The positivity rate was the highest in whole blood specimens (68.6%). Typing data were only available for 4 cases: type 40 (n = 1), type 41 (n = 2), and type other (n = 1).

Of the 204 cases PCR tested for SARS-CoV-2, 24 (11.8%) tested positive. Serology results for SARS-CoV-2 were only available for 34 cases, of which 23 (67.6%) had a positive finding. Of the 72 cases with data on COVID-19 vaccination, 61 (84.7%) were unvaccinated.

Introduction
------------
Purpose and scope:
This report provides an overview of the cases of hepatitis of unknown origin in children aged 16 years and below reported to ECDC and the WHO Regional Office for Europe for the period up to [Tue 31 May 2022], through The European Surveillance System (TESSy). Figures and tables describe national case-based data for surveillance of hepatitis of unknown origin in children aged 16 years and below from all the countries and areas of the WHO European Region, including the 27 countries of the European Union (EU) and the additional 3 countries of the European Economic Area (EEA).

Since the first alert launched by the UK on [Tue 5 Apr 2022], cases of hepatitis of unknown etiology in children have been reported from multiple countries worldwide. It is not yet clear whether all cases identified following the alert are part of a true increase compared to the baseline rate of hepatitis of unknown etiology in children.

The etiology and pathogenetic mechanisms of disease are still under investigation. A possible association with current adenovirus infection has been identified, but other hypotheses and possible co-factors are under investigation. Most cases continue to be reported as sporadic, unrelated cases. Data are submitted through the case-based record type NOVHEP to The European Surveillance System (TESSy) database hosted at ECDC.

Case Definition:
Cases of hepatitis of unknown origin should be reported to TESSy if they meet any of the following criteria:

Probable: A person presenting with an acute hepatitis (non-hepatitis viruses A, B, C, D and E*) with aspartate transaminase (AST) or alanine transaminase (ALT) over 500 IU/L, who is 16 years old or younger, since 1 Oct 2021.
Epi-linked: A person presenting with an acute hepatitis (non-hepatitis viruses A, B, C, D and E*) of any age who is a close contact of a probable case since 1 Oct 2021.
Discarded: A subject previously classified as case, that following further investigations did not meet the case definition criteria.
*Cases of hepatitis with known etiology such those due to specific infectious diseases, drug toxicity, metabolic hereditary, or autoimmune disorders should not be reported under this protocol.

Note that the UK local case definition includes only cases younger than 16 years which means cases aged 16 years are not reported to TESSy from the UK.

