******
[6] Singapore
Date: Tue 31 May 2022
Source: The Straits Times [edited]
https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/another-two-acute-hepatitis-patients-aged-3-and-8-identified-from-last-year-cause-is-unknown-moh


Review of records finds 2 more kids with acute hepatitis last year; infant with the illness in April has recovered
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Two retrospective cases of acute hepatitis of unknown causes have been identified. A 3-year-old developed the illness last October [2021], and an 8-year-old got it last November [2021], said the Ministry of Health (MOH) on Tuesday [31 May 2022]. After laboratory testing, the 2 cases were found to be negative for the common hepatitis viruses, such as hepatitis type A, B, C and E viruses.

Both children did not have a history of COVID-19 infection prior to their acute hepatitis, and they continue to be under regular follow-up.

The look-back investigation comes after MOH asked all hospitals with pediatric services to review their patient records for those who have similar signs and symptoms as the cases reported by the WHO, which raised the alert on acute hepatitis of unknown cause occurring in young children overseas.

As at [26 May 2022], 650 probable cases have been reported to WHO from 33 countries, with 99 additional cases pending classification, according to the WHO study.

Hepatitis in young children is not uncommon and it is not unusual for the cause of some hepatitis cases in children to remain unknown, said MOH.

"Thus far, MOH has not observed any unusual increase or pattern in the number of children with hepatitis of unknown cause," the ministry said. On [30 Apr 2022], MOH reported a case of acute hepatitis of unknown cause in a 10-month-old infant. The infant has since been discharged and is currently well, said MOH on Tuesday [31 May 2022].

It added that the cause of acute hepatitis remains unknown. MOH added: "While the cause of hepatitis in all 3 cases has not been identified, it may not mean that these cases are linked to the global outbreak. We continue to monitor the situation closely and have informed all medical practitioners to be vigilant for young children presenting with signs and symptoms of hepatitis for which a cause cannot be identified."

[Byline: Rosalind Ang]

